AB Both face-to-face communication and communication in online environments
   convey information beyond the actual verbal message. In a traditional
   face-to-face conversation, paralanguage, or the ancillary meaning- and
   emotion-laden aspects of speech that are not actual verbal prose, gives
   contextual information that allows interactors to more appropriately
   understand the message being conveyed. In this paper, we conceptualize
   textual paralanguage (TPL), which we define as written manifestations of
   nonverbal audible, tactile, and visual elements that supplement or
   replace written language and that can be expressed through words,
   symbols, images, punctuation, demarcations, or any combination of these
   elements. We develop a typology of textual paralanguage using data from
   Twitter, Facebook, and Instagram. We present a conceptual framework of
   antecedents and consequences of brands' use of textual paralanguage.
   Implications for theory and practice are discussed. Published by
   Elsevier Inc. on behalf of Society for Consumer Psychology.
