   different types of resources. To address this, we introduce a
   self-regulatory model of resource scarcity. In it, we propose that
   consumers respond to resource scarcity through two distinct
   psychological pathways: a scarcity-reduction route aimed at reducing the
   discrepancy in resources and a control-restoration route aimed at
   reestablishing diminished personal control by attaining security in
   other domains. We explain how a key determinant of which route the
   consumer will pursue is the perceived mutability of the resource
   discrepancy. We also specify moderators, based on our proposed model, to
   identify when each of the two routes is pursued. This model is assessed
   in the context of alternative theoretical perspectives, including
   commodity theory, life history theory, and models of compensatory
   behavior. Finally, we provide a research agenda for those interested in
   studying the psychology of resource scarcity from a self-regulatory
