   using moderation tasks and biometric feedback. Furthermore, we
   demonstrate that compensation has an immediate dampening effect on
   arousal intensity. Thus, if consumers can compensate before explicitly
   evaluating an extremely incongruent product, their evaluations tend not
   to be negative. Taken together, we document that extreme innovations
   encourage compensation, and in compensating, consumers can become more
   receptive to extreme innovations.
